{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"64de9c03-98cb-4967-9ad3-c509b8b3c0cc","content":"The project directory doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a `dotnet tool`:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<Project Sdk=\"Microsoft.NET.Sdk\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n    <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n    <!-- dotnet tool packaging -->\n    <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n    <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n    <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n    <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n    <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n    <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n    <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n    <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n    <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n\n  <!-- Include a README in the package -->\n  <ItemGroup>\n    <None Include=\"README.md\" Pack=\"true\" PackagePath=\"/\"/>\n  </ItemGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|----------|---------|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the package as a global/local dotnet tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users invoke (e.g., `my-mcp-server`) |\n| `OutputType=Exe` | Required — tools must be executables |\n\n### Publishing steps\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server  # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThe critical piece is `PackAsTool=true` — everything else is standard NuGet metadata.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b4dbb37a-26ed-438a-a0e5-ff8cba195340","outputTokens":538,"requestId":"2018:204067:1730EA1:19E2EF2:6A0522AF"},"id":"59c0cc51-48ac-4071-a39f-a9fdd60764ed","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:17:45.